function numMatchingSubseq(s, words) {
    const positions = Array.from({ length: 26 }, () => []);

    for (let i = 0; i < s.length; ++i) {
        positions[s.charCodeAt(i) - 'a'.charCodeAt(0)].push(i);
    }

    let count = 0;

    words.forEach(word => {
        let index = -1;
        let isSubsequence = true;

        for (let i = 0; i < word.length; i++) {
            const c = word.charCodeAt(i) - 'a'.charCodeAt(0);
            const pos = positions[c].find(el => el > index);
            if (pos === undefined) {
                isSubsequence = false;
                break;
            }
            index = pos;
        }

        if (isSubsequence) {
            count++;
        }
    });

    return count;
}
```

    For each character in string s, we save its position in an array (positions) which maps characters to their positions. Specifically, we use one array for each character ('a'-'z').

Now for each word in words array, we traverse its characters one by one. We check if there is a position for each character greater than the last checked position. If we are successful in finding such positions for every character in the word, we increase the count.

We do this using the positions array, which has sorted positions of each character.

We use the 'upper_bound' function in C++ and 'bisect_left' function in Python to find the smallest number greater than a given number in a sorted list of numbers. In Java and JavaScript, we use a loop to search for the number manually.

Finally, we return the count.

